occur during spinal shock?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Loss of tendon reflexes","Increased anal tone","Hyperreflexia below the lesion","Increased sympathetic outflow","Hypertension"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring spinal shock, there is temporary loss of all reflex activity below the level of injury. \u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of tendon reflexes\u003C/strong\u003E is a characteristic finding, along with flaccid paralysis and autonomic dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased anal tone\u003C/strong\u003E - Anal tone is decreased or absent during spinal shock due to loss of reflex activity\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperreflexia below the lesion\u003C/strong\u003E - Reflexes are absent during spinal shock; hyperreflexia develops later\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased sympathetic outflow\u003C/strong\u003E - Sympathetic activity is decreased during spinal shock\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertension\u003C/strong\u003E - Blood pressure is typically low due to loss of sympathetic tone\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpinal shock lasts hours to weeks and is characterised by areflexia, flaccid paralysis, and loss of autonomic function below the level of injury. After spinal shock resolves, spastic paralysis and hyperreflexia develop.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Spinal shock causes temporary loss of all reflexes and flaccid paralysis below the level of injury.","Spinal shock typically includes decreased sympathetic outflow leading to hypotension.","During spinal shock, anal tone is decreased or absent."],"references":["Malhotra M, Bhatoe HS, Sudambrekar SM. Spinal Cord Injuries. Med J Armed Forces India. 2010 Oct;66(4):325-8. doi: 10.1016/S0377-1237(10)80009-7. Epub 2011 Jul 21. PMID: 27365735; PMCID: PMC4919809.","Hagen EM. Acute complications of spinal cord injuries. World J Orthop. 2015 Jan 18;6(1):17-23. doi: 10.5312/wjo.v6.i1.17. PMID: 25621207; PMCID: PMC4303786.","Ziu E, Weisbrod LJ, Mesfin FB. Spinal Shock. 2024 Feb 12. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28846241."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61253"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16829"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61253"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-31T12:53:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-31T12:53:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9520"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75740"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}